        "text": "#### Indications\n- Patients requiring an adrenaline infusion.\n\n#### Procedure\n\n- Medication checks are to be done by two officers prior to administration.\n\n- Adhere to all aseptic techniques.\n\n- Inject **1mg of adrenaline into a 500ml** bag of saline via the access port.\n\n- Fill out and attach an additive label to the fluid bag.\n\n- Connect a giving set or a burette to the fluid bag. \n- **If you are using a giving set:** ensure the gate clamps are turned off prior to inserting into the fluid bag.\n- **If you are using a burette:** connect a giving set to the bottom of the burette and ensure all gate clamps are turned off prior to inserting into the fluid bag. Now open the ventilation port then the gate clamp and fill the burette to the 100ml mark. Open the gate clamp and prime the line and then refill the burette to the 100ml mark.\n\n- Connect the giving set to the patient and commence infusion. \n- 20 drops/minute = 1ml per minute or 2 mcg/minute\n- Titrate for a response.\n\n- Reassess respiratory and perfusion status.\n\n#### Contraindications\n- Nil when indicated.\n\n#### Specific Notes\n- Ensure that all of the delivery lines are primed with adrenaline. Failure to do this will result in a in a significant delay in the patient receiving adrenaline.\n- If the adrenaline infusion is running through an IO line, you may require a pump set rather than a giving set to overcome increased intra medullar pressure.",
