      {
        "text": "##### Type\nHypertonic alkaline solution – 8.4% sodium bicarbonate solution. Contains 1mMol/ml sodium and 1mMol/ml bicarbonate [no schedule]\n\n- **High-risk medication**\n\n##### Presentations\n50ml sodium bicarbonate solution – glass vial\n\n##### Actions\n\n- Neutralises metabolic acidosis as a result of cardiac arrest or poor perfusion \n\n- Causes movement of K+ into cells – swaps with H+ ions\n\nOnset IV: 30 – 60 seconds.\n\n#### Uses\n\n- Cardiac arrest secondary to cardioactive drug overdose or hyperkalaemia \n\n- Prolonged cardiac arrest (>15 minutes) \n\n- For emergency treatment of hyperkalaemia \n\n- For treatment of arrhythmias, seizures or coma in overdose of cardioactive medications (e.g., tricyclics antidepressant, \\u03b2 blocker, digoxin) \n\n- To combat acidosis and hyperkalaemia in crush syndrome \n\n#### Adverse Effects\n\n- Metabolic alkalosis\n\n- High sodium content may lead to fluid overload and cardiac failure \n\n- Interacts with some other drugs (especially calcium and adrenaline): \n- always flush well through the line before and after administration\n- consider a second line\n\n#### Contraindications\nKnown hypersensitivity \n\n#### Pregnancy and Breastfeeding##### Pregnancy\n- Safe to use\n\n##### Breastfeeding\n- Safe to use\n\n#### Doses#### In cardiac arrest\n**Secondary to hyperkalaemia or cardioactive drug overdose; prolonged arrest >15 minutes**\n##### Adult and Paediatric\n- **ICP: **1mMol/kg IV or IO \n- Fast push\n- No repeat.\n\n#### Hyperkalaemia with cardiac output ##### Adult and Paediatric\n- **ICP: **0.5mMol/kg IV or IO \n- Over 2 to 5 minutes\n- May repeat once, if required.\n\n#### Cardio-active medication overdose##### Adult and Paediatric (12 lead with wide QRS complex)\n- **ICP: **1mMol/kg IV or IO \n- Over 30 to 60 seconds\n- May repeat once, if required. \n\n#### Special Notes\n- Always administer sodium bicarbonate to cardioactive medication overdose patients when in cardiac arrest.",
